y hopes of their epic has to ask themselves and many can drive themselves slightly balmy trying to answer it. <br><br>After many discussions with my friends (/wave supacheal) where the logic of the situation was presented in a variety of different ways I chose to keep leveling. The biggest reason for this is that our epic isn't very defining for us where as it can be very defining for other classes. Our epic doesn't contribute to a raid in a vast and awe inspiring way like a cleric or enchanter epic does. Our epic doesn't make us any better at taunting or tanking like a warrior epic does. It's proc doesn't serve a highly useful purpose like the rogue or ranger epic does. The list goes on, the pal and sk epics are basically very pretty 2hs weapons that allow you to bash. Does that mean you should abandon the goal? Not in the slightest. But because you can find numerous 2hs weapons and 1hs + shield combos that will more than make up the damage, taunt, interupting ability and many times the looks of the FA/FD it is silly to keep it as your primary goal. Our roll as paladins has been defined as damage spounge first, damage dealers second, and casters third (and if you've ever seen a paladins logs, you know just how sad that is.) So do what you need to do to fit your roll and don't allow an epic hilt to sidetrack you with obsession. If you're going to obsess about gear, worry about your AC/HP. If you need to have goals, think towards divine glory, divine aura, superior heal, resurrection, divine strength. Just do the day to day and some day the gods will smile on you. There was a post on PoN a while back with a screenshot of a Gorenaire killing that dropped 3 frost books simultaneously. It's a sight that most paladins could cry to see and most guilds would groan to see heh. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Point is it does happen. <br> <p><A HREF="http://www.m